  "id": "T1036_010_txt_1",
  "content": "ID: T1036.010\nTitle: Masquerading:Masquerade Account Name\nURL: https://attack.mitre.org/techniques/T1036/010\nAdversaries may match or approximate the names of legitimate accounts to make newly created ones appear benign. This will typically occur during Create Account , although accounts may also be renamed at a later date. This may also coincide with Account Access Removal if the actor first deletes an account before re-creating one with the same name. [1] Often, adversaries will attempt to masquerade as service accounts, such as those associated with legitimate software, data backups, or container cluster management. [2] [3] They may also give accounts generic, trustworthy names, such as \"admin\", \"help\", or \"root.\" [4] Sometimes adversaries may model account names off of those already existing in the system, as a follow-on behavior to Account Discovery . Note that this is distinct from Impersonation , which describes impersonating specific trusted individuals or organizations, rather than user or service account names.",
  "category": "Article",
  "source": "Local Storage",
